Having composed two books of Algebra, he had extended his plan so as to embrace the whole art of Logistic; and the nominate part of his Algebra would probably have merged in his third book called Geometrical Logistic, while the second book of Algebra, which he called the positive or cossic part, in which unknown quantities are treated of under fictitious representa- tione, would have formed the fourth and last book of his great digest of Numbers. It is quite consistent with the nature of the subject to suppose, that the reason why Napier's book of the Logistic of concrete quantities by concrete numbers termi- nates abruptly, and why no other fragment of it could be found, was, that at this stage of his speculatione, he had set himself to the invention of Logarithms, which may indeed be considered as the grand result of the Logistic of concrete
